review_text: I don‚Äôt know about this but I want to like it. I picked this up today and tried it for the first time ten minutes ago. Eyecream - there was a flash of heat when applying this but only on my upper cheek are towards the outside of my eyes and not towards the inner corners of my eyes. It overlapped with other products in other areas but only had the reaction in one spot (the same spot for both sides). I‚Äôm assuming I‚Äôve damaged my skin barrier in the same spot on both sides of my face either by exfoliating or my make up application is removing my SPF. Resurfacing night serum - it stung going over any broken skin but not when it went over the cheek area that came in contact with the eye cream. Omega repair cream - more of a watery formula that went on smoothly and let me use a controlled amount to cover face, neck and chest in one go. As a lot of users here seemed to have difficulty getting the product to dispense, so did I UNTIL I READ THE DIRECTIONS ‚Äî SEE BELOW:To open:Remove the cap, slide down the clear plastic sleeve, and remove the yellow pin from the center of the brush.Twist the body of the brush from the closed position to open.Tilt and tap the brush gently against your wrist until the powder flows through the bristles.Use powder generously to reapply your UV protection.To close:Twist the body of the brush from the open position to closed, being careful not to twist beyond the closed position.Pull up the clear plastic sleeve and snap the cap back on.Once I did this, I had no issues with product dispensing, or coming out after using. review_text: I purchased this product from the Glossier website as a set with a 1oz bottle of Futuredew (pro tip: Glossier‚Äôs products are a fair amount cheaper if you purchase them as sets, so I would find products you like and match them with a set that contains all/most of them!). It is very gentle and smooth, but I‚Äôm still not too sure how effective it really is. It is really good at removing obvious makeup/dirt/impurities from the previous night if there‚Äôs any remaining, but you don‚Äôt get that ‚Äúsqueaky clean‚Äú feeling that you would get from a product like the Kiehl‚Äôs cleanser. That said, it is kind of nice that this product feels almost moisturizing, as opposed to drying, since some cleansers feel that way on the skin! It has a very subtle but nice rose scent, so it‚Äôs technically not fragrance-free, but I read in the ingredients that the fragrance is ‚Äúunder 1% and formulated without Acetaldehyde, Acetone, Acetonitrile, Benzalkonium chloride, BPA, EDTA, Methylene chloride, PTFE, PFOA‚Äú, so it shouldn‚Äôt be overwhelming to most people. Additionally, I have to give props to how this product is Clean at Sephora, cruelty-free, vegan, and formulated without sulfates SLS and SLES - I‚Äôm very glad how Sephora has made an effort to bring in more clean beauty products/brands - especially such a mainstream one like Glossier!All in all, a 6oz bottle of this cleanser lasted me just under a year, which is really good considering I used two pumps of this 1-2 times a day. It‚Äôs not the cheapest cleanser at $19, but I would say if you‚Äôre looking for a gentle cleanser that feels soft on the skin, I would splurge on this. However, if you‚Äôre looking for a sudsy, more ‚Äúsqueaky clean‚Äú feeling cleanser that strips skin of everything (potentially including a bit of moisture, if you‚Äôre okay with that), I‚Äôd go with something else.

I‚Äôve used this since the first formulation debuted in 2010 (plastic bottle hihihi), and I‚Äôve gone through the multiple iterations since then (literally almost a hundred bottles total I would estimate). They‚Äôve undergone a few reformulations but it just keeps getting worse. I would have to say that they‚Äôve completely lost their touch with this serum. Every other year, they seem to knock down the concetration of the more expensive, active ingredients, while increasing the amount of cheaper, horrible formulation fillers. And the gag is: they keep raising the price despite the horrendous/cheaper reformulations. When I first started purchasing, it was around $98 for a 1oz... just a few months ago it was $135... and now it‚Äôs risen to $145? The greed at french houses like Dior is absolute nuts and they really think consumers are that blindly dumb to continue purchasing, especially in this economy. Unfortunately I‚Äôm going to have to start looking elsewhere for a replacement daily serum (it‚Äôll be a pretty easy task with all of the comparable if not better options on the market lol) because everything about One Essential has gone downhill. I‚Äôm really loving these. I worked for a dermatologist for 10 years and am very familiar with dermaplaning practices. I‚Äôd say this is a great product for beginners, especially if a spa/derm isn‚Äôt in your budget or of any interest. The most important thing is the angle at which you hold the razor and not performing this too frequently (over-exfoliation is a def a thing). Make sure you‚Äôre always holding the razor at a 45-degree angle against your skin. Short downward strokes are the best way to go when you‚Äôre dermaplaning at home after you cleanse and dry your face. Keeping the skin taut and moving from top to bottom is the general rule of thumb. Take it slow too and be conscious of the unique angles/curves of your face. Dermaplaning is a very intuitive practice! I‚Äôd recommend only doing it every 3 to 4 weeks for optimal results. Afterward, avoid direct sun exposure/extreme heat for a few days days, don‚Äôt use scrubs or other exfoliators for a week, avoid chlorine on your face for a week, apply serums, moisturizers, and sunscreen as usual.

review_text: To preface this, I‚Äôm usually not one to splurge on various serums that claim to purify/clarify/any-verb-that-helps-your-skin-ify...especially not three different ones, but when I saw the Glossier Super Serums marked down from $67 to $87 when sold as a pack (and even cheaper during the Black Friday Sale, I had to try them). Firstly, this 1oz bottle is adorable, with minimalist aesthetic packaging, a cute baby-blueish liquid in a clear glass bottle, and a tiny dropper. But don‚Äôt let the size of this product fool you - it is effective with only 3-4 drops per day, so this bottle has lasted me for over a year! Additionally, this product is vegan, cruelty-free, and Clean at Sephora, which is quite impressive. I use this product daily after I shower, in between toner and moisturizer. I simply drop 3-4 drops in my hand, and then spread it around my face. It is very lightweight on the skin, and there‚Äôs no burning/sticky feeling that you can get with other serums. I then wait 30 seconds before applying my moisturizer.After a couple days of using this product, I noticed that my face had not only become smoother, but a lot of redness was gone as well - even and especially in the morning right after I had woken up! But the true test was when a blotchy blemish showed up after a couple of days of vacation where I hadn‚Äôt taken Super Pure with me - when I returned, I just used the serum as usual, and within a couple of HOURS, the blemish was gone.So no, this serum isn‚Äôt the cheapest, but I would say that you need surprisingly little for it to work, and it works quite well. In comparison, I‚Äôve tried The Ordinary‚Äôs Niacinamide 10% + Zinc 1% Oil Control Serum (which is a quarter of the price), and I think that that product also works quite well for redness, blemishes, and general skin-tone care, but it leaves a kind of sticky feeling on my skin. So if you‚Äôre comfortable making the splurge, go with this product, but if not, The Ordinary is a great alternative.

Alkyl glucosides used and still technically are considered mild and gentle BUT several years ago were found to actually be allergens that can cause allergic dermatitis reactions. Literally won allergen of the year in 2017. You can google the studies. While a lot of people won‚Äôt have reactions many don‚Äôt realise that the reason they are breaking out in bumps, redness, little white heads all over is from a reaction to glucosides in products. They are in so many amazing products from all brands and all types of products because it‚Äôs still considered gen√©rele and mild but just know that if you are prone to contact dermatitis, have a compromised skin barrier, or sensitive skin in general you should try your best to shy away from glucosides. The most commonly used being decyl glucoside. If you‚Äôre one of many that have used Glow recipe and loved the result but not the reaction of breakout you got. Check the list. It‚Äôs in the eye cream etc. you might have less of a reaction with rinse offs such as cleansers BUT studies show that you should refrain from even using rinse offs because of worsening future reactions. Hoping this helps people who have had issues with skincare and can‚Äôt seem to figure out what the ingredient is. Glucosides come up in search as being safe for sensitive skin until you keep researching. A lot of sunscreens use it as well and it‚Äôs not always the uva/uvb ingredient irritating your skin.
review_title: Warning for contact dermatitis and sensitive skin!

review_text: I first heard about this product when I saw the famed make-up artist Bobbi Brown talking about how she stopped wearing foundation because she has been using it. Then I heard one of the Kardashian sisters talking about it as well. Now I‚Äôm not a celebrity crazy person. I understand they are paid to say these things but still I was curious. Bobbi Brown has her own skin care line so for her to unofficially endorse another brand says a lot. But then I saw the price and I was like ‚Äúuh, that‚Äôs okay.‚ÄúThen 4 months ago I got a sample from Sephora for an order I had placed. I figured it‚Äôs free-what‚Äôs the worst that can happen. Full discloser I‚Äôve been using Lancome‚Äôs Genefique for about 20 years-and I swear by this stuff. I also use SKII‚Äôs essence and their night cream-religiously.I will say this product with one use makes my face look like I just had an oxygen facial. If you want to experiment then try this-just use the A.B. The Rich Cream around your eyes only. (Our eyes are the first place where aging starts-around the age of 24-25 years old) This way you have something to compare it to. Now the sample last me about 3 months-I used it every day. So for those who are on the fence because of the steep price-the stuff goes a long way and it‚Äôs super concentrated. You only need a tiny bit of it. The pores about my T-zone have shrunk to almost normal size. (I have large pores around my nose from teenage acne. I‚Äôve tried everything to shrink it from laser therapy to prescription Retinol. Nothing seem to quite work) The Rich Cream also has minimize the scars from my nose from surgery I had 2 years ago and the fine lines around my eyes has gotten softer. I now only use the A.B. system. It‚Äôs pricy but think of all the hundreds of dollars we all have thrown away trying out products that seem to work for a while or never worked as advertise. I know I have a drawer full of them. I‚Äôm telling you-it‚Äôs worth the hype! You won‚Äôt reget it.

The Rich Cream gives noticeable results and this is a great value. Normally the cream itself is $180, so it‚Äôs like getting the other two products for $5.  Is it pricey? Yes. It also performs, so in my opinion, it‚Äôs worth it.
